	(458, 1, '2018-04-05 10:11:26', '2018-04-05 03:11:26', '<strong>Rối loạn cương</strong><strong> </strong>(từ tiếng anh Erectile dysfunction) là rối loạn tình dục, đặc điểm là không có khả năng khởi phát hay duy trì cương cứng của dương vật trong quá trình giao hợp.\r\n\r\nNguyên nhân cơ học thường gặp là bệnh tim mạch và bệnh tiểu đường, bệnh thần kinh, sự khiếm khuyết về nội tiết.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNguyên nhân tâm lý là dương vật không đủ cứng do những suy nghĩ hay cảm giác hơn là những khó khăn cơ học, đặc biệt trong dạng này những thuốc giả dược nhiều khi có tác dụng.\r\n\r\nRLC liên quan chủ yếu tới sức khỏe nói chung xuống dốc, hoặc thói quen ăn uống không tốt, béo phì, đặc biệt bệnh tim mạch, bệnh mạch vành và bệnh mạch máu ngoại biên.\r\n\r\nMột cách đơn giản để phân biệt RLC chức năng hay thực thể là xác định xem bệnh nhân đã từng có RLC chưa. Nếu chưa bao giờ thì có thể là thực thể; nếu thỉnh thoảng có bệnh có thể là thực thể hoặc chức năng.\r\n\r\nSiêu âm Duppler để đánh giá dòng máu, dò tĩnh mạch, dấu hiệu của xơ vữa động mạch, sẹo hay can-xi hoá thể cương.\r\n\r\nViệc điều trị chủ yếu bằng nội khoa.', 'Rối loạn cương là gì?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '408-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-04-05 10:11:26', '2018-04-05 03:11:26', '', 408, 'http://news.aigiupminhkhong.vn/2018/04/05/408-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
	(172, 1, '2018-03-29 10:11:15', '2018-03-29 10:11:15', 'The term is derived from the name of the town of Spa, Belgium, whose name is known back to Roman times, when the location was called <i>Aquae Spadanae</i>, sometimes incorrectly connected to the Latin word “spargere” meaning to scatter, sprinkle or moisten. The word spa itself denotes “fountain”. Some experts also suggest that the word “spa” originated from the name of the Belgian town named Spa where a curative natural spring was discovered in the 14th century. Since medieval times, illnesses caused by iron deficiency were treated by drinking chalybeate (iron-bearing) spring water (in 1326, the ironmaster Collin le Loup claimed a cure, when the spring was called <i>Espa</i>, a Walloon word for "fountain").\r\n\r\nIn 16th-century England, the old Roman ideas of medicinal bathing were revived at towns like Bath (<i>not</i> the source of the word bath), and in 1596 William Slingsby who had been to the Belgian town (which he called <i>Spaw</i>) discovered a chalybeate spring in Yorkshire. He built an enclosed well at what became known as Harrogate, the first resort in England for drinking medicinal waters, then in 1596 Dr Timothy Bright after discovering a second well called the resort <i>The English Spaw</i>, beginning the use of the word <i>Spa</i> as a generic description.\r\n\r\nIt is commonly claimed, in a commercial context, that the word is an acronym of various Latin phrases such as "<i>Salus Per Aquam</i>" or "<i>Sanitas Per Aquam</i>" meaning "health through water". This is very unlikely: the derivation does not appear before the early 21st century and is probably a backronym as there is no evidence of acronyms passing into the language before the 20th century; nor does it match the known Roman name for the location.', 'Adam Health Care', 'Experience the Art of Caring', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '9-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-29 10:11:15', '2018-03-29 10:11:15', '', 9, 'http://news.aigiupminhkhong.vn/2018/03/29/9-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
	(128, 1, '2018-03-28 10:08:17', '2018-03-28 10:08:17', 'The term is derived from the name of the town of Spa, Belgium, whose name is known back to Roman times, when the location was called <i>Aquae Spadanae</i>, sometimes incorrectly connected to the Latin word “spargere” meaning to scatter, sprinkle or moisten. The word spa itself denotes “fountain”. Some experts also suggest that the word “spa” originated from the name of the Belgian town named Spa where a curative natural spring was discovered in the 14th century. Since medieval times, illnesses caused by iron deficiency were treated by drinking chalybeate (iron-bearing) spring water (in 1326, the ironmaster Collin le Loup claimed a cure, when the spring was called <i>Espa</i>, a Walloon word for "fountain").\r\n\r\nIn 16th-century England, the old Roman ideas of medicinal bathing were revived at towns like Bath (<i>not</i> the source of the word bath), and in 1596 William Slingsby who had been to the Belgian town (which he called <i>Spaw</i>) discovered a chalybeate spring in Yorkshire. He built an enclosed well at what became known as Harrogate, the first resort in England for drinking medicinal waters, then in 1596 Dr Timothy Bright after discovering a second well called the resort <i>The English Spaw</i>, beginning the use of the word <i>Spa</i> as a generic description.\r\n\r\nIt is commonly claimed, in a commercial context, that the word is an acronym of various Latin phrases such as "<i>Salus Per Aquam</i>" or "<i>Sanitas Per Aquam</i>" meaning "health through water". This is very unlikely: the derivation does not appear before the early 21st century and is probably a backronym as there is no evidence of acronyms passing into the language before the 20th century; nor does it match the known Roman name for the location.', 'Phòng khám Nam Khoa', 'Experience the Art of Caring', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '9-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-28 10:08:17', '2018-03-28 10:08:17', '', 9, 'http://news.aigiup